<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: GARDEN GROVE; PARAMEDIC TEAM ADDED TO TRASK AVENUE FIRE 
STATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A paramedic team has joined the fire station on Trask Avenue to serve 
residents in the city's southeast area. 
</P>
<P>
 Fire Chief Vincent Bonacker said the addition this week of a paramedic team at 
Fire Station No. 3 at 12132 Trask Ave. means four of the city's seven fire 
stations now have paramedics. 
</P>
<P>
 A paramedic team consists of a captain, an engineer who drives the fire engine 
and a paramedic-firefighter. 
</P>
<P>
 Bonacker said that the team at Fire Station No. 3 will not involve additional 
expense because a trained paramedic will be added to an existing engine 
company.  
</P>
<P>
 Bonacker said that it is part of the Fire Department's effort to meet the 
increasing demand for emergency medical assistance, which makes up a majority 
of calls to the fire stations. 
</P>
<P>
 The paramedic, also a trained firefighter, will be responsible for operating 
emergency medical equipment and evaluating the condition of patients before the 
arrival of regular paramedics. 
</P>
<P>
 "This will help reduce medical emergency response times and increase the level 
of service at no additional cost," Bonacker said. 
</P>
<P>
 There are paramedic teams at the Fire Department headquarters on Acacia 
Parkway, Station No. 2 at 11805 Gilbert Avenue and Station No. 5 at 12751 
Western Ave. 
</P>
<P>
 The 93-member Garden Grove Fire Department has 23 paramedics. It does not have 
its own ambulance service but contracts with Southland Life Fleet, a private 
company based in Anaheim.BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</TEXT>
