<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH COURT REFUSES SHILEY APPEAL CASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday declined to review the dismissal of an appeal 
that would have challenged a $215-million court settlement reached two years 
ago in the Shiley heart valve case. 
</P>
<P>
 The decision clears the way for payments to more than 50,000 recipients of 
potentially defective heart valves made by Irvine-based Shiley, a unit of 
Pfizer Inc. in New York. 
</P>
<P>
 The settlement, reached in U.S. District Court in Cincinnati, also includes 
money for research into detection of defective valves and an advisory panel to 
issue guidelines that could help patients implanted with the devices. 
</P>
<P>
 James Capretz, a Newport Beach lawyer who won an undisclosed settlement for 
about 300 heart-valve recipients in Orange County Superior Court last year, 
said Monday that "the Cincinnati case is of major significance to Pfizer and 
thousands of implantees. This final dismissal by the Supreme Court is extremely 
important." 
</P>
</TEXT>
